{"id": "duc04-testb-2:0#1", "contents": "Hodler's allegations came as the IOC continued investigations into alleged financial misconduct by the Salt Lake City group that won the bid for the 2002 games. He described a $500,000 scholarship fund set up by Salt Lake, which benefited the relatives of six IOC members, as a \"bribe.\" Hodler also questioned the integrity of the voting process for the 1996 Atlanta Games and the 2000 Sydney Olympics, stating that he would be surprised if Sydney's election was clean. He added that he knew what happened but did not want to disclose it, saying \"I can't imagine that Sydney is different from the others.\""}
